What are some things that you notice about this histogram?

Exploring with Bin Width

Notes:

  • Changing the bin width can reveal interesting patterns in the data.

Adjusting the Bin Width

Notes:

qplot(x = friend_count, data = pf, binwidth = 25) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0, 1000))

ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 25) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50))

Faceting Friend Count

# What code would you add to create a facet the histogram by gender?
# Add it to the code below.
qplot(x = friend_count, data = pf, binwidth = 10) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000),
                       breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) +
    facet_wrap(~ gender)

Omitting NA Values

Notes:

  • NA is an encoding for missing values
qplot(x = friend_count, data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), binwidth = 10) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000),
                       breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) +
    facet_wrap(~ gender)

Tenure

Notes:

ggplot(aes(x = tenure), data = pf) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 30, color = 'black', fill = '#099DD9')

How would you create a histogram of tenure by year?

ggplot(aes(x = tenure / 365), data = pf) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 8),
                       breaks = seq(0, 8, 1)) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.25, color = 'black', fill = '#F79420')

Labeling Plots

Notes:

  • The plots should speak for themselves
ggplot(aes(x = tenure / 365), data = pf) +
    xlab("Number of years using Facebook") +
    ylab("Number of users in sample") +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 8),
                       breaks = seq(0, 8, 1)) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.25, color = 'black', fill = '#F79420')

library(gridExtra)
## Warning: package 'gridExtra' was built under R version 3.1.2
## Loading required package: grid
p1 <- ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) +
    xlab("Friend count") +
    ylab("Number of users in sample") +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 100, color = 'black', fill = '#5760AB')
p2 <- ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) +
    xlab("Friend count") +
    ylab("Number of users in sample") +
    scale_x_log10() +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.2, color = 'black', fill = '#5760AB')
p3 <- ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) +
    xlab("Friend count") +
    ylab("Number of users in sample") +
    scale_x_sqrt() +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 2, color = 'black', fill = '#5760AB')

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3)

Add a Scaling Layer

Notes:

  • scales can be added to existing plots(DRY)
  • be careful with the axis names when adding scales
countScale <- ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) +
    geom_histogram() +
    scale_x_log10()

logScale <- qplot(x = log10(friend_count), data = pf)

grid.arrange(countScale, logScale, ncol = 2)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

Frequency Polygons

qplot(x = friend_count,
      data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)),
      binwidth = 10) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000),
                       breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) +
    facet_wrap(~ gender)

qplot(x = friend_count, y = ..count../sum(..count..),
      data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)),
      xlab = "Friend Count",
      ylab = "Proportion of Users with that friend count",
      geom = "freqpoly", binwidth = 10, color = gender) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000),
                       breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50))
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_path).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

ggplot(aes(x = friend_count, y = ..count../sum(..count..)), data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_freqpoly(aes(color = gender)) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) +
  xlab('Friend Count') +
  ylab('Percentage of users with that friend count')

Likes on the Web

Notes:

  • the ticks on the log scale are from the normal plot
ggplot(aes(x = www_likes), data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_freqpoly(aes(color = gender)) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  xlab('Likes Count') +
  ylab('Count of users with that like count')
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

ggplot(aes(x = log10(www_likes)), data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_freqpoly(aes(color = gender)) +
  scale_x_continuous()+
  xlab('Likes Count') +
  ylab('Count of users with that like count')

ggplot(aes(x = www_likes, y = ..count../sum(..count..)), data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_freqpoly(aes(color = gender), binwidth = 1000) +
  scale_x_continuous() +
  xlab('Likes Count') +
  ylab('Percentage of users with that like count')
